  "text": "The potential for exercise to prevent the development of chronic pain is understudied, although clinical evidence supports that the prevalence of chronic pain is lower among individuals with a history of regular exercise. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] The strikingly persistent attenuation of allodynia by prior voluntary wheel running raises several questions, including how much exercise is required for protection. We found that the distance travelled did not correlate with allodynia after CCI (Tables S1-3, available online as supplemental digital content at http://links.lww.com/PAIN/ A276). Indeed, there was wide variability in the total distance run. For example, in the final week, rats varied in the distance run from 4 to 23 km, yet all rats exhibited suppression of neuropathic pain. These data suggest that neuropathic pain protection is a function of regular exercise across time, rather than the amount of running per se. This is in accord with other studies that find that the total distance traveled in voluntary wheel running does not predict the magnitude of effect on other endpoints, which suggests that even a small amount of voluntary exercise regularly performed over time can have dramatic effects. [CITATION_3] Other groups have investigated the impact of varying the overall duration of regular exercise. Two weeks of treadmill running or 3 weeks of voluntary wheel running before CCI or low thoracic contusion spinal cord injury, respectively, was not sufficient to attenuate the subsequent development of nociceptive hypersensitivity. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] However, it is not clear whether these differing results are due to the shorter duration of exercise, or the mechanistic differences between exercise paradigms or injury models. Although 8 weeks of prior voluntary wheel running prevented initial hind paw allodynia in an acidic saline model of chronic pain, the effect Table 1 Prior voluntary wheel running attenuates macrophage infiltration into the sciatic nerve, proximal to the injury site. Table 2 Prior voluntary wheel running attenuates macrophage infiltration into the sciatic nerve, distal to the injury site. % area positive, assessed at 3 and 14 day after CCI/sham surgery.",
